Introduction

In this vignette we demonstrate how to use PATH to measure categorical cell state phylogenetic correlations and how to infer cell state transition dynamics on phylogenies simulated as a sampled somatic evolutionary process. For a similar analysis using idealized phylogenies, or a more in depth introduction of how we model cell state transition dynamics, see this vignette. For more information, see our bioRxiv preprint.

Somatic evolution

Here, we demonstrate PATH as in the section above, but instead of analyzing idealized phylogenies, we use phylogenies simulated as a sampled somatic evolutionary process. The process used to simulate these phylogenies, while more complex than the one above, is likely a better representation of somatic evolution, as cell birth and death occur stochastically, and the phylogeny represents a sample of the total somatic population.

Here, we first randomly generate the transition rate matrix \(\mathbf{Q}\) using the PATH function rQ(), by specifying the number of cell states \(n\) with the function’s first argument. Here we use this function to randomly generate a \(3\)-dimensional transition rate matrix and use expm to get the transition probability matrix.

Simulate

We then use ran_tree_with_states() to simulate a phylogeny using a sampled somatic evolutionary process, and set the number of sampled cells to be N = 1000, with a sampling rate of rho = 10^-3, meaning that the total simulated somatic population contains one million extant cells at the time of sampling.


Q <- rQ(3, 0.1)
P <- expm(Q)
# Simulate phylogeny (phy1) with a sampled somatic evolutionary process
# using specified transition rate matrix (Q0), cell number (N), and
# cell sampling fraction (rho).
phy1 <- ran_tree_with_states(Q0 = Q, N = 1000, rho = 10^-3)

We can visualize this phylogeny and annotate the cells by their state.

Measure phylogenetic correlations

As was done here, we compute phylogenetic correlations using xcor(), after first computing a normalized phylogenetic weight matrix with one_node_tree_dist(), and by reformatting the cell state vector into a matrix with catMat().

# Get phylogenetic node distance matrix 
# retaining only node distances of 1.
W <- one_node_tree_dist(phy1)

# Transform vector of cell state assignments into matrix
# format for calculating phylogenetic correlations. 
X <- catMat(phy1$states)

# Compute phylogenetic correlations with xcor().
# Output of xcor() is a list,  including:
# phylogenetic correlations ("Morans.I"), and
# leaf-permutation based
# analytical z scores ("Z.score"), 
# variance ("Var.I"), expected values ("Expected.I"),
# and one-sided p-values ("one.sided.pvalue").
phy1xcor <- xcor(X, W)

We use phylogenetic auto-correlations as a measure of cell state clustering, or heritability, and the concordant z scores to assess statistical significance. Both auto-correlations diag(phy0xcor$phy_cor) and z scores diag(phy0xcor$Z.scores) are plotted below.

The phylogenetic relationships between cell states as quantified with phylogenetic cross-correlations phy0xcor$phy_cor can be visualized as a heat map, as below. Note that the diagonal of the heat map represents the same values as depicted in the auto-correlation bar plot above.

Infer cell state dynamics

Finally, we can use these phylogenetic correlations to infer cell state state transition dynamics with the function PATH_inf(). This function takes a phylogeny (here, phy0), the name of the cell state vector (here, "states" as cell states are stored at phy0$states), and nstates, the number of possible cell states.

We use two different inference approaches. The first inference uses measured, and the second uses imputed (imputed_branches = TRUE), branch length distances (the distance in units of time between cells separated by a node distance of one). Branch length imputation can be useful if we suspect that measured branch lengths are inaccurate or if missing.

# Infer cell state transition probabilities from phylogenetic
# correlations and measured branch lengths using PATH.
Pinf <- PATH_inf(tree = phy1, cell_states = "states", nstates = nrow(P))

# Infer cell state transition probabilities from phylogenetic
# correlations and imputed branch lengths using PATH.
# Note that our sampling rate estimate (sample_rate_est) of 10^-2 
# is incorrect, as the simulated (true) sampling rate is 10^-3. 
Pinf.impute <- PATH_inf(tree = phy1, cell_states = "states", nstates = nrow(P),
                         impute_branches = TRUE, sample_rate_est = 10^-2)

First we can see what the inferred transition probabilities are for a length of time proportional to the branch length distances separating cell pairs one node apart.

# PATH-inferred transitions for time corresponding to a node depth of 1
Pinf$Pt
#>      1    2    3
#> 1 0.49 0.27 0.23
#> 2 0.35 0.39 0.26
#> 3 0.21 0.18 0.61

PATH uses the above transition probability to estimate \(\mathbf{P}\) for a time-step of \(t=1\).

We can compare inferred transitions to the true simulated transitions, for \(t=1\).

# PATH-inferred transitions using measured branch lengths (t=1)
Pinf$P
#>       1     2    3
#> 1 0.908 0.061 0.03
#> 2 0.079 0.881 0.04
#> 3 0.027 0.028 0.95

# PATH-inferred transitions using imputed branch lengths (t=1)
Pinf.impute$P
#>       1     2     3
#> 1 0.871 0.085 0.043
#> 2 0.110 0.833 0.057
#> 3 0.039 0.039 0.922

# True transitions (t=1)
P
#>       [,1]  [,2]  [,3]
#> [1,] 0.890 0.083 0.027
#> [2,] 0.045 0.884 0.071
#> [3,] 0.030 0.031 0.939
